Keywords: Coherence; Volatility; Business Cycles; Time Series
length: 22 pages
abstract: This paper studies the relationship between international trade and output 
    fluctuations. The authors find evidence that the business cycles of countries 
    that are more open to international trade are more likely to by synchronized 
    with the business cycles of their major trading partners. A detailed study of 
    the South Korean case shows that while business cycles are related to openness, 
    the diversification of export destinations seems to weaken these links. The 
    authors find no relationship between openness and output volatility.
